file-name: XC597327-Large-tailed Nightjar-calssical calls-4-4-Xeno-Ipoh, Perak, Malaysia-24th October 2020.mp3
rmk:
These posts are to discuss the different calls and song made by the Large-tailed Nightjar. I am attempting to summarise observations over many years. Note that we have had a male Large-tailed Nightjar live with us in very close proximity for 2.5 years (day time roost in the garden) which only stopped earlier this year. This bird has become very accustomed to us and allows close observation of behaviour at other time, even 4-6am when with a mate. 
These are a number of calls/song made. 
The commonest sounds heard are the frequent territorial calls given in short bursts of 1-4 notes or in long continuous bouts for several minutes. They are described by various individual as “tok, tok, tok” (HBW 2020) or “tchonk” (Wells 1999). We think of them as the “chock-chock” calls. These are heard more often during the breeding season, and for my home we hear them more commonly from October to February. HBW describes these as the bird’s ‘song’. They have, what I call, and inverted-flag type sonogram. There is a sharp rise to the note followed by a decrescendo drag to the call. The notes last 0.2 seconds and are often repeated in couplets. Although loud they are only of 5 kilohertz (kHz) frequency. 
The second most often heard calls are softer ‘growling’ notes. These are most commonly used during courtship with a response from the partner. These notes last 0.1-0.2 seconds and are very low frequency of 1-2kHz. 
The third type of calls is the least common and hardest to record. They occur at the start of a bout of calls, may not be repeated often, and hence can be easily missed. This sequence of calling, or call structure, is one I have heard many times over the years. I call these calls the introductory or initiating calls. Usually 3-5 of these are given before a few growling notes and then a launch into the classical “chock-chock” calls. They are a low frequency 1.5 kHz calls made in a couplet of 3-4 notes. 
This recording 4 shows the entire call structure when calls are being initiated, as described above. Starting with the introductory notes, then low level growls followed by the explosive ‘song’. All 3 types of calls in sequence.

file-name: XC597326-Large-tailed Nightjar-mating calls-3-3-Xeno-Ipoh, Perak, Malaysia-24th October 2020.mp3
rmk:
These posts are to discuss the different calls and song made by the Large-tailed Nightjar. I am attempting to summarise observations over many years. Note that we have had a male Large-tailed Nightjar live with us in very close proximity for 2.5 years (day time roost in the garden) which only stopped earlier this year. This bird has become very accustomed to us and allows close observation of behaviour at other time, even 4-6am when with a mate. 
These are a number of calls/song made. 
These are the second most often heard calls are softer ‘growling’ notes. These are most commonly used during courtship with a response from the partner. These calls can carry on for long periods. For example, this morning I was woken up by the calls just before 4am and continued to hear them, with short breaks, until 5.45am. The growling calls are initiated by the male and, after a short while, the female joins in. The female is initially further way but slowly comes closer, until the pair is less than 0.5 meter apart. There are some brief aerial displays while the calls are going on. There is a wave pattern to their mutual-growling-courtship calls – a crescendo-decrescendo nature – where the calls become louder and softer and louder again. The calls become a tight synchronised duet which may be an important element in the mating or bonding process. Recording from this morning showed 186 notes per minute. The notes last 0.1-0.2 seconds and are very low frequency of 1-2kHz.

rmk:
Single individual was calling from a metal wall/fence

HPF = -6dB
Normalize = -3dB

The Large-tailed Nightjar that initially lived in our immediate neighbourhood and, for the past 2 years, has lived in our garden, is probably the bird we have watched the most. Apart from frequent daytime observations, we also get to watch night time behaviour before our bedtime and especially when we have breakfast on our roof in the early mornings (4.30-5.30am). 
One interesting observation is courtship calls – when the pair is courting they will make low pitched growling calls to each other as part of the bonding process. These are very different from the loud, classical “chock-chock” calls. The mutual-growling-courtship activity can carry on for long periods. In one 50 second continual recording, I counted 120 vocalisations (2.4 per second, counting only the louder partner, recorded at 5.30am). Amplified recording here. You have to listen intently to hear the partner vocalising almost simultaneously in the ‘background’. When the first caller pauses briefly you can hear and identify the other bird’s calls. The sonogram in the post shows how low pitched the calls are at 1-2.5 kHz.

rmk:
The bird was in canopy in a Longan grove adjacent to my home....approx. 10-12m. away from the house.
I think it may be the Long-tailed Nightjar, Caprimulgus macrurus, but I have no experience hearing them.
I think I may have been hearing it, much subdued from inside the house, for some time before realizing that it must be a bird and not a human-generated sound at that hour in our quite quiet surroundings.
After making the recording with my iPhone voice memo app, the sound continued until about  23:30.

Previously published on AVoCet as AV4162. Certainty: less than 100%. ID determined by: not specifically indicated; recordist normally sees birds recorded and indicates if any question. Ed: this is very different from other C. macrurus, e.g. large number on XC. GPS: http://population.mongabay.com/population/timor-leste/1945443/los-palos. Habitat: forest edge.

Recording information: No modification to the call was done.
Habitat: Montane mossy forest
Behavior: One bird was seen feeding in the mossy undergrowth, below a female snowy-browed flycatcher. It was not calling until we identified it as a pygmy wren babbler and played its 3-note song. However, the bird responded with this call instead and subsequently, we only heard this call along the trail and identified them to be made by the pygmy wren babbler.

Two white-morph birds were heard singing their typical two-note whistle song here.  A possible breeding pair as they were found foraging together and responding to each other’s song. On noticing our presence both birds uttered this ‘chizzup-chizzup-chizzup’ alarm call very different from its other known vocalisations, perhaps suggesting commencement of nesting activity (?). This is a cut from one of the birds. Habitat: boulders,  dense undergrowth beside a roadside rivulet.

loc: Trail to Krung Ching Waterfall, Khao Luang National Park

rmk: Witnessed a pairof adults duetting. The birds were perched less than 50cm apart on a log, facing each other. One bird was calling facing up while swinging its neck left and right, while the other was facing the calling bird and flickering its wings (similar to the movements a begging juvenile makes, but less aggressive). They later flew to another log and continued the same process. After about 3 minutes one bird disappeared and the other bird continued foraging quietly. The foraging bird was so confiding it hopped up to within 1 metres of us, completely unperturbed by our presence. At one point it even perched at the edge of the trail.

Thanks to a Xeno-Canto user Yeo SB I have reviewed this recording and agree with him that it is a Short-Tailed Babbler which often occurs in exactly the same spot and (I have since realised) occasionally makes this call at dusk.  There was another Siberian Blue Robin wintering here this year (2020) and during numerous encounters we only heard a simple 'tick' call

PLEASE HELP -  TRYING TO SPOT THIS BIRD IS DRIVING ME MAD!  

This bird is ubiquitous, but incredibly elusive. It spends its time in the canopy, is often heard, but never seen. At least 4 of them visit our garden almost every day. Their calls all vary slightly in tone. I have recorded all of them.

They are very active most mornings from around 5 until 8 am., then in the afternoons from around 4 - 5:30. They are sometimes heard in the early afternoon as well.

PLEASE HELP!

rmk:
The mobile phone recording was not modified in any way other than conversion from m4a to MP3.

The species, of which there are at least 4 individuals nearby, is very vocal around sunrise and occasionally during the day, particularly mid to late afternoon.

The habitat is mixed tree cover in a long thin green belt immediately behind our garden in the centre of the city close to the botanical gardens. The species seems to perch close to the canopy.

It is often heard, but until now has never been seen.

rmk:
This unknown call was taken from the Rainforest Discovery Centre in Sepilok. No sightings to go with it I'm afraid. 

Whilst trekking around the rain-forest there were often bird calls that were coming from deeper into the forest than I could see .. or the birds were closer but just not visible in the canopy. I'm hoping someone can recognise at least some of these to assuage my curiosity !

1. Note that I have amplified some of the tracks and others have had to be converted from WAV files to MP3s to comply with the forum maximum file sizes. 

2. Note that the unknown bird song I'm enquiring about is the background bird (the foreground bird only calls a couple of times)

3. All calls were unsolicited

4. All calls recorded on an Olympus LS-14. 

5. WAV files are available.

Thanks !
Kevin

El ecosistema consiste en un arroyo seco en la mayor parte de su recorrido, pero la cercanía del nivel freático a la superficie permite la existencia de bosques de álamo, tarajales y carrizal que aunque han sido eliminados en gran parte aún quedan fragmentos. Más allá hay un mosaico de pinar, olivares, algunos restos de alcornocal-encinar, viñedos y cultivos de leguminosas y cereal.

loc: Singinawa Jungle Lodge, outskirts of Kanha Tiger Reserve, near Baihar, Balaghat, Madhya Pradesh
rmk: A pair of Greater Racket-tailed Drongos were seen as a part of mixed flock, which included several Jungle Babblers, a pair of Greater Coucals, three Black-hooded Orioles, single Rufous Treepie and a single Large-billed/Indian Jungle Crow. The entire flock seemed alerted, usually the way they get in the presence of a predator such as an owlet, a cat or a snake, but no predator was seen.
